rComments: I loved Ana because she was so approachable and willing to help. She would always check on the students as she was lecturing to make sure that what she was teaching made sense to the class. Plenty of practice questions and lots of time to discuss every topic in detail. Very sweet woman!

The exams are very predictable -- she makes you practice the same things over and over in class and it's the same exercises in the exams. Very easy if you follow in class. She is adorable but a little boring.. Tiny textbook, an interesting read although not very necessary to ace the class.

She is one of the nicest people you will ever meet but also one of the worst professors. She unclear and difficult to find outside of class mostly because she's never on campus. Tests are easy and relate directly to class material which is great but the final exam made absolutely no sense and she gave no help at all.
She's somewhat sloppy (makes mistakes on the board) and unavailable. But she knows her material and picks out the important threads for lectures etc quite well. Mixed feelings here.

An extremely intelligent woman, passionate about linguistics. Textbook was extremely confusing, but she did a fantastic job of pulling out the main points of the material, and had great illustrating examples. Also did a good job making sure the students were actually keeping up and grasping the material before moving on. A little brusque at times.

Amazing prof and class (Intro to languages)! Hyper-intelligent, eloquent and engaging. She ensures that the class understands the material and discusses the material at length. Yes you have to read Pinker and understand him, but re-read it if you don't get it. One of my favorite courses thus far.

a very smart professor, too smart for the average first year university student who knows squat about linguistics. Her test questions are hard to understand and she makes you read a text that is very hard to grasp. She is a nice lady but when it comes to teaching, I would rather take a class with another professor who makes the material easier

A very sweet women. But not a good Prof. I think the problem is she is waaaaaaay too enthusiastic about Linguistics and she knows so much about it, she thinks that she is making her point across to her students. The prob is, she is not. Incomprehensible. Quizes reflect the text and class material but questions are ambiguousFInd another PROF not ana

Has a lil accent and a soft voice so in a classroom setting, its not the best. Keep up w/ chapter readings, because the class textbook is basically an expansion of her class notes..& the quizzes are  based on the book & notes. She has reading guides which help you focus on the more imp. info in each chap. Overall ok teacher, i would recommend her!

Nice and seems to care, but she is very unavailable and tells people to talk to the T.A (I'm too busy). You're a PROF, that's your job. Her exams use trickery and test comprehension of poorly drafted questions rather than course material. Very inflexible and not open to student suggestions.
nice but demanding :-)
What the heck is she talking about again? Incomprehensible in any language. She's unclear as to pretty much everything and never answers e-mails. Never again, thanks.

i am seriously disturbed if she's considered one of the best profs out there.  the only thing that got me through the classes was my long methodical process of eating a grapefruit with a fork.  it was a painful class.  "uh huh"

Definately agree with the below. She is very slow at putting notes on the web! She requires us to attend class but hardly uses her lectures on the tests. We have to read a whole novel on our own. Always late to class, complains that her eyes are hurting...S heesh, not helpful, doesn't answer emails or her office door. She should not teach anymore!
She's ridiculously terrible.  Never prepared, absent a lot, slow on putting anything on the website, and she says UH-HUH way too much.  No use for her AT ALL.  She should be fired.
"uh-huh"
This is a mind-bending topic in Linguistics, but Ana was able to break the basics into manageable pieces to start gaining an appreciation.

A terrific prof. You probably need to really like the class material to appreciate her teaching, but I thought she was very knowledgable and passionate. The class structure, including tests, is pretty informal, but she makes things very obvious. Her English is not that bad. All in all, you won't get a better prof.
She is really funny and goofy, and pretty entertaining. The final was open book. She takes things directly from the textbook, so as long as you read it, you are pretty much guaranteed an A.

ana is a fairly good prof. as mentioned before, she does encourage questions, and is always willing to help.  i didnt find her to be arrogant, in fact she was pretty funny and she practically gives you the tests in her reading guides! i recommend her!
The tests are bizarrely designed, but she is always willing to answer questions about the content of the course, and encourages the class to think critically about the material presented.

Ana is a very nice and helpful prof. She really want everyone in the class to do well. She is pretty funny when she is rolling her eyes at the class (if everyone in the class is dumb). The only problem is sometimes her accent is very thick and she speks in broken english. but she puts EVERYTHING online. She is a good prof!
Not too bad, she's nice but this class is so useless
I don't really feel like I learned anything in Semantics II, and I don't think I'll ever use Semantics in real life, but Ana is a great prof and really goes out of her way to help her students.

She is the most arrogant prof in the university but she knows how to hide it...I think she underestimates everyone around her and she thinks she is the best. Her class was hard to follow because she wanted to show us how smart she is...
Ana simply rocks. She's an extremely knowledgeable, intelligent, clever, lively and spirited lady who will teach you like you've never been tought before. You go girl!
